bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Elizabeth Burtner (1906-2009) was a professor of dance at The George Washington University. She is credited with introducing modern dance into the curriculum, increasing dance performances, and organizing more dance groups. Burtner graduated from Hood College in 1927 with a bachelor's degree in Dance, and received a master's degree from Columbia University in 1935. She studied at Bennington College, New York University, with the Humphrey Weidman Group, the Martha Graham School , and other New York Studios. She preformed with the Evelyn Davis Dance Ensemble in Washington, D.C. She joined the faculty of GW in 1938 as a dance instructor and archery coach in the Physical Education Department.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection contains programs, brochures, clippings, scripts, sketches, notes, correspondence, press releases, scores, research materials, biographies, and photographs. The material dates from 1903-2003, and was collected by Elizabeth Burtner in the course of her career as professor of dance at The George Washington University. The collection contains both materials relating specifically to GW's dance program, and materials relating to trends in dance and prominent dancers.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into two series: Dance program at The George Washington University and Dancers and trends in dance.

did.unittitle: Dance program at The George Washington University

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains materials related to Burtner's work as a professor of dance at The George Washington University. Most of the materials, including programs, clippings, scripts, sketches, notes, correspondence, press releases, scores, research materials, photographs, were arranged by Burtner into albums by topic. Burtner's arrangement has been preserved. Photographs have been placed in separate folders directly behind the materials with which they were originally filed. The bulk of the series consists of materials related to performances given by Orchesis and Dance Production Groups. These materials are arranged by the performance (e.g., Annual Spring Concert, Carnival, Homecoming, etc.). Schedules, budgets, programs, correspondence, and memoranda relating to the administration of Orchesis and Dance Production Groups are included as well. This series also contains materials, such as clipping, programs, and correspondence, related to noteworthy dance students and their careers subsequent to their study at The George Washington University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains clippings, subject files about dance notation, specific performers, choreographers, and dance companies, and theatrical and souvenir programs. Burtner compiled chronological files of newspaper and magazine clippings about dancers, trends in dance, and dance performances. Additional clippings, as well as brochures, biographies, photographs, promotional materials, and correspondence are included in the dancer subject files. The Laban Art of Movement Guild magazine and other newsletters and publications are included in the dance notation subject files.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Text on photograph: "U.S. Department of State Magazine Reprint Unit, IPS-IIA WP-52 MR-53-S-95 All Dance Is Contemporary Martha Graham, one of the foremost dancers in the United States, is shown here in the role of Emily Dickinson in "Letter to the World," which she created some years ago and revived in April 1952. Miss Graham in discussing her work says that all dancing is contemporary and that freedom of thought for the individual is necessary in the creative arts. Miss Graham's discussion of the dance is of particular interest since she has created a number of new dance roles and has established a system of teaching dance which has been copied widely. (50-2722)"

Considered the finest in her profession, her originality and inventivemenss have made it possible for her to develop a new medium of communication."

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Text on photograph: "U. S. Information Agency Magazine Reprints, IPS WP-275 MR-55-S-41 Doris Humphrey: Yesterday and Today 1. One of the group of young dancers who evolved a personal dance language in the 1920's and 1930's, Doris Humphrey is shown here in a movement study taken when the Humphrey-Weidman Compnay was in residence at Mills College in California. Of her work Miss Humphrey has said, 'I wish my dance to reflect some experience of my own in relationship to the outside world; to be based on reality illumined by imagination ... and to make its contribution toward the drama of life.' (55-872)"

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Text on photograph: "U. S. Information Agency, Magazine Reprints, IPS WF-275 MR-55-S-41 Doris Humphrey: Yesterday and Today 2. Gaiety is the prevailing mood of 'Exhibition Piece, ' created by Doris Humphrey in 1931. Here she is shown with Charles Weidman, left andJose Limon in one of the movements of that dance. Miss Humphrey has an impressive list of compositions to her credit. She was awarded a Guggenheim Fellowship in 1949 to write a book on choreography and in 1953 received the Capezie Dance Awared for her creative leadership in the modern dance. (55-873)"

odd.p: Transcript (partial) of oral history interview with Elizabeth Burtner conducted by Miss. Theresa Bowers for the Columbia University Oral History Research office. The interview was conducted in the Holiday Inn in Washington, D.C.,on September 30, 1979. The interview is one of a series documenting the Bennington Summer School of the Dance. The portion in this file appears to be a copy with corrections possibly by Ms. Burtner.
